Since the pandemic began, it sent my OCD into overdrive.

I fear normal every day things that I didn’t really fear over before. It sent my anxiety into an absolute snowball effect of what felt like life and death.

Things I overcame this year:

• I didn’t really go out in public for nearly 2 years atleast leisure shopping. I did a lot of grocery pickups in my car, online shopping, etc in fear of being around others

• flying on a plane - obvious because fear of flying but also being trapped in a steel machine circulating other peoples breath 😵‍💫 with a toddler who can’t mask 

• said flight canceled and stuck in an airport for 10 hours while severely sleep deprived and exhausted I had no choice but to nap on the floor. I have bad contamination ocd and germs are not my friend. This was actually an exposure therapy homework from my therapist and guess what I did it!! And I survived to tell the story 🤪

• went to a Halloween event where there was a large crowd - my fear of shootings and violence was extremely overwhelming but I didn’t let it stop us from having fun and creating memories. Another exposure therapy checked off the list!

• last but definitely not least, since the pandemic I hadn’t been sick since 2019. Talking with my therapist I realized I started to equate any sickness to automatic death. Knowing I’d eventually be exposed to sickness, I knew with each time I’d become stronger and remember that sickness is normal and often times east to overcome. I’ve been sick about 3 times this year and it has eased some anxiety but I still struggle heavily.

This is a reminder that recovery is not easy, but it IS worth the journey. ERP therapy has been so hugely beneficial in my recovery and I’m still on my journey through it.

YOU CAN DO HARD THINGS! 🫂🤍✨

hear me out - recovery is the hardest thing you can choose but the best decision you can make 🦋

Recovery looks different to every person. When I started recovery I didn’t know what to do, no handbook on “how to recover” or recovery for dummies book. I started recovery for my mental health. I knew wanted a change and I HAD to commit myself to it fully. 100% - and I didn’t realize just how hard it be but just how much more rewarding it would be.

Recovery isn’t something you choose once, it’s something you have to keep choosing everyday. Choosing recovery to me means choosing the best version of yourself. Choosing recovery means accepting what is, getting help, taking control of your life and trying to live the life that you deserve despite your illness or disorder.

All in all if you want to make a change in your life, I urge you to jump to it. Whether it’s recovery or not - making positive changes in your life is so freeing. Breaking away from bad habits, negative people, toxic emotions you carry daily. You are in control of making this decision and if you have no support in this, you have me. 🫂 

You don’t have to be alone in your struggles in life. You just have to have the right people around you supporting, encouraging and loving you through every phase. 

You have nothing to lose and everything to gain from recovery 🦋✨🫶🏼 I promise you it’s WORTH IT 🫂

I’ve been told my whole life I’m sensitive, dramatic, broken, fragile; therefore no one could ever want to be with me.

My name is Becca. I am extremely passionate about mental illness awareness and ending the stigma on mental health. Due to the stigma and lack of awareness, I was in the dark for many years feeling alone, unsure of who I was and feeling different. I want to preface this by saying: I am NOT defined by my illnesses! I currently am in therapy and have been for over a decade! It has been a saving grace in my recovery. While I am privileged to be able to afford and access therapy, this is not the case for everyone and this NEEDS to change. I am also currently on medication to manage my anxiety/ocd.

The name BetteringBecca was birthed when I dedicated myself to my mental health recovery and promised to better myself mentally no matter how hard things got.

Lack of hygiene is more common than is spoken about with those who live with mental illnesses like depression.

You are not lazy.
You are not dirty.
You are not a failure.
You are not a bad person for being unable to keep up with these things during depressive episodes or seasons.

It’s okay to ask for help. It’s okay to hire a service to help clean (there are even specific services that cater to those specifically with mental illnesses so you don’t have to carry the burden of shame, guilt or embarrassment).

Recovery brought me here 🌈

About 10 years ago, I was diagnosed with agoraphobia.

Agoraphobia is the fear of places and situations that might cause panic or helplessness. I was terrified of going into crowds (in the fear of dying) and grocery stores (in the fear of having a panic attack).

After working through this extensively in psychotherapy - I prevailed. For years that never even crossed my mind.

Until 2020, with the pandemic, the increase in gun violence and mass shootings. Sickness, death and panic. It’s all I could think about when I was awake and dream about when I was sleeping.

There were many times I missed out on huge life events, because I was scared. I was isolated in fear of sickness or death. I missed out on fun memories I could have created in fear of a possibility. 

I have had dreams of dying hundreds of times. Only to fuel my anxiety even more to be engulfed by agoraphobia again.

For nearly a year and a half I barely ever left my apartment. 

Working through ERP (exposure therapy) has been life changing. In the past week I went to my first baseball game, a light event at night in an area I didn’t know where I was and my first red rocks concert with nearly 10 thousand people.

This is what recovery has brought me ❤️‍🩹

Scrolling through socials last night. I saw a video of a woman showing trauma healing (somatic responses by shaking) it’s proven to help regulate the nervous system.

This video was stitched by a large creator essentially making fun of her by getting a phone call of bad news, pulling out a tripod and pretending to cry and immediately stopping after. Again, in response to the woman’s video.

I get it’s very taboo to see a video of someone crying or showing any distressed emotions; and you may judge on first sight. You have no idea why they may record themselves. I’ve had my absolute fair share of hate comments. 

“You’re just doing this to seek attention”
“Who records themselves crying, you’re pathetic”
“You’re weak”

Every human feels emotions. Whether you show them or not, doesn’t make them never exist. I record my crying, bpd episodes, or anything related to my mental health because trauma is proven to take your memories. I don’t have the greatest memory due to trauma. It sucks. But documenting my healing journey shows me how far I have come. I look at happy videos in my bad days and able to stomach my bad videos on my good days. This reminds me I can and already have overcome the darkest days and I can still push through.

It may not make sense to you, and that’s fine!!!! You don’t have to do it if it doesn’t work for you. But don’t judge others healing process. Seeing comments like these are absolutely gut wrenching. These are the same people who are struggling themselves but projecting hurt and it’s never okay.

We can’t act surprised when we lose loved ones by suicide, because we “never saw the signs”. You did. You just chose to ignore them, judge them, shame them, shut them out. We can’t ask others to come to us when they need help, and judge how they display their symptoms. We can’t advocate for mental health, but choose which illnesses. 

Suicide prevention starts with YOU. Accept, love, support and be there no matter what. 🫂

I never knew this was linked to OCD until I began ERP therapy and now I’m not allowed to google 🥹

(Well, I’m not supposed to anyways).

In my OCD recovery, I am working on my health ocd. This specific subtype of OCD has completely ruled my life at times.

Days where I’d literally wake up and spend hours (yes hours) googling symptoms I had. Diving deeper and deeper into a hole I dug myself. It got so bad to the point where I’d spend all day panicking, crying and full of fear that I now have cancer, I’d imagine planning my funeral, decided what to tell my daughter and imagining my families life without me. All for very common symptoms.

That mixed with spamming my doctors with messages of “is this normal?” “Should I be worried?” “When can I come in again?” Visiting urgent cares and ER’s on monthly basis. 

I knew this wasn’t healthy and I needed it to stop. It was exhausting. I could never live in the moment. In fear of what’s next?

In ERP therapy (exposure and response prevention), my therapists rule is - you are allowed to check *one* time. Go to the doctor, do the tests, if you are cleared there’s no need to check again and again and again.

The thing about OCD is it thrives off reassurance - and even worse; the reassurance is very short lived. The 5 minutes after a doctor tells you “everything looks great the scans are clear” you feel relief. Then the fear creeps in. What if they missed something? What if I have a rare case they don’t know about? What if the machine wasn’t working right?

OCD is a beast, but I promise you recovery is worth it. Checking only makes things worse. Reassurance feeds the OCD. Please know you don’t have to live this way forever 🤍

While I’m not 100% better yet, I have made incredible strides in my OCD recovery!!

Walking with my mental health 🧠🚶‍♀️✨ 
Part 2

Almost didn’t, but so glad I did.

Trust me when I say I totally understand the mental gymnastics of wanting to do something good for yourself and your mental health - but not having the mental energy to do it. 

Try the five second rule. Count to 5 and get up on 5. Call your doctor, clean that space in your room, make yourself food, move your body - apply it to anything. After that 5 seconds if you don’t get up you probably won’t do the thing.
